commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor AddressBook initialization to use constructor
commitResults.messageBody:
Refactor AddressBook initialization to use constructor instead of non-static block

- Removed the non-static initialization block for the 'persons' field in AddressBook.
- Moved initialization of 'persons' to the constructor for improved code clarity and maintainability.
- This change follows modern Java best practices and makes the initialization logic more explicit.
- Used deep copy to ensure immutability
This is to allow undo feature to create a deep copy (new isolated references) of the current person list state, which will then be used to recover the list when undo is invoked

- First label commands that are mutable (add, clear, delete, edit)
- Give those commands an undo function to be called to revert the effect
- Mutable function are pushed to a history stack
- Undo function pop the history stack and call the command's undo function
- Undo-ed function pushed in to the undo stack
- Redo function pop the undo stack and execute the command again

commitResults.messageTitle: Find command: support partial multi-field search
commitResults.messageBody:
The find feature matches only by name, requiring full-word matches. This
limits usability when agents remember only partial names or have other
identifiers such as phone numbers or email domains.

Enable flexible lookups so users can locate clients by partial,
case-insensitive matches across name, phone, and email.

Let's

add ClientMatchesPredicate to perform OR-based, partial,
case-insensitive checks over name/phone/email

update FindCommand to use the new predicate and to pass parsed
keywords to the model for future UI highlighting

This approach keeps the existing predicate-driven architecture, avoids
storage changes, and maintains backward compatibility with model APIs.

commitResults.messageBody:
The help system only opens the external User Guide link, which forces
users to leave the app to check command usage details.

A built-in help system improves usability by allowing users to learn
commands directly within the app.

Let's add a new 'man' command that provides inline manuals for all
commands in the result display panel. Each command now includes a
MANUAL entry describing its name, usage, parameters, examples, and a
link to the full User Guide.

This improves onboarding and user self-sufficiency by offering concise,
contextual help without depending solely on the external guide.

commitResults.messageTitle: Set the max number tag constraint
Ensure that EditCommand will respect the max tag constraint
Limit tags per person to 15 to prevent UI lag
commitResults.messageBody:
When a person has an extremely large number of tags (e.g. 100k),
the application experiences severe performance degradation when
rendering the tag list, making scrolling and interaction laggy.

To address this, a hard limit of 15 tags per person is enforced
at both parsing and edit time:
* Added Person.MAX_TAGS_PER_PERSON = 15 constant
* Added validation in ParserUtil.parseTags() to reject >15 tags
* Added validation in EditCommand#createEditedPerson() to guard
  against tag overflow after editing
* Added unit tests for over-limit add and edit scenarios

This ensures consistent performance and prevents
inputs from degrading the UI experience.
